<doc id="1188375" wikidata="Q4489310" url="?curid=1188375" title="Turing reduction">
<text>In computability theory, a Turing reduction from a decision problem formula_1 to a decision problem formula_2 is an oracle machine that decides problem formula_1 given an oracle for formula_2 (Rogers 1967, Soare 1987) in finitely many steps. It can be understood as an algorithm that could be used to solve formula_1 if it had access to a subroutine for solving formula_2. The concept can be analogously applied to function problems.

If a Turing reduction from formula_1 to formula_2 exists, then every algorithm for formula_2 can be used to produce an algorithm for formula_1, by inserting the algorithm for formula_2 at each place where the oracle machine computing formula_1 queries the oracle for formula_2. However, because the oracle machine may query the oracle a large number of times, the resulting algorithm may require more time asymptotically than either the algorithm for formula_2 or the oracle machine computing formula_1. A Turing reduction in which the oracle machine runs in polynomial time is known as a [[polynomial-time reduction#Turing reductions|Cook reduction]].

The first formal definition of relative computability, then called relative reducibility, was given by Alan Turing in 1939 in terms of oracle machines. Later in 1943 and 1952 Stephen Kleene defined an equivalent concept in terms of recursive functions. In 1944 Emil Post used the term &quot;Turing reducibility&quot; to refer to the concept.

== Definition ==

Given two sets formula_16 of natural numbers, we say formula_1 is Turing reducible to formula_2 and write
:formula_19
if and only if there is an oracle machine that computes the characteristic function of &quot;A&quot; when run with oracle &quot;B&quot;. In this case, we also say &quot;A&quot; is B&quot;-recursive and B&quot;-computable.

If there is an oracle machine that, when run with oracle &quot;B&quot;, computes a partial function with domain &quot;A&quot;, then &quot;A&quot; is said to be B&quot;-recursively enumerable and B&quot;-computably enumerable.

We say formula_1 is Turing equivalent to formula_2 and write formula_22 if both formula_19 and formula_24 The equivalence classes of Turing equivalent sets are called Turing degrees. The Turing degree of a set formula_25 is written formula_26.

Given a set formula_27, a set formula_28 is called Turing hard for formula_29 if formula_30 for all formula_31. If additionally formula_32 then formula_1 is called Turing complete for formula_29.

===Relation of Turing completeness to computational universality===
Turing completeness, as just defined above, corresponds only partially to Turing completeness in the sense of computational universality. Specifically, a Turing machine is a universal Turing machine if its halting problem (i.e., the set of inputs for which it eventually halts) is many-one complete for the set formula_29 of recursively enumerable sets. Thus, a necessary &quot;but insufficient&quot; condition for a machine to be computationally universal, is that the machine&#x27;s halting problem be Turing-complete for formula_29. Insufficient because it may still be the case that, the language accepted by the machine is not itself recursively enumerable.

== Example ==

Let formula_37 denote the set of input values for which the Turing machine with index &quot;e&quot; halts. Then the sets formula_38 and formula_39 are Turing equivalent (here formula_40 denotes an effective pairing function). A reduction showing formula_19 can be constructed using the fact that formula_42. Given a pair formula_43, a new index formula_44 can be constructed using the smn theorem such that the program coded by formula_44 ignores its input and merely simulates the computation of the machine with index &quot;e&quot; on input &quot;n&quot;. In particular, the machine with index formula_44 either halts on every input or halts on no input. Thus formula_47 holds for all &quot;e&quot; and &quot;n&quot;. Because the function &quot;i&quot; is computable, this shows formula_48. The reductions presented here are not only Turing reductions but &quot;many-one reductions&quot;, discussed below.

== Properties ==

* Every set is Turing equivalent to its complement.
* Every computable set is Turing reducible to every other set. Because any computable set can be computed with no oracle, it can be computed by an oracle machine that ignores the given oracle.
* The relation formula_49 is transitive: if formula_19 and formula_51 then formula_52. Moreover, formula_53 holds for every set &quot;A&quot;, and thus the relation formula_49 is a preorder (it is not a partial order because formula_19 and formula_56 does not necessarily imply formula_57).
* There are pairs of sets formula_58 such that &quot;A&quot; is not Turing reducible to &quot;B&quot; and &quot;B&quot; is not Turing reducible to &quot;A&quot;. Thus formula_49 is not a total order.
* There are infinite decreasing sequences of sets under formula_49. Thus this relation is not well-founded.
* Every set is Turing reducible to its own Turing jump, but the Turing jump of a set is never Turing reducible to the original set.

== The use of a reduction ==

Since every reduction from a set formula_1 to a set formula_2 has to determine whether a single element is in formula_1 in only finitely many steps, it can only make finitely many queries of membership in the set formula_2. When the amount of information about the set formula_2 used to compute a single bit of formula_1 is discussed, this is made precise by the &quot;use&quot; function. Formally, the &quot;use&quot; of a reduction is the function that sends each natural number formula_67 to the largest natural number formula_68 whose membership in the set formula_2 was queried by the reduction while determining the membership of formula_67 in formula_1.

== Stronger reductions ==

There are two common ways of producing reductions stronger than Turing reducibility. The first way is to limit the number and manner of oracle queries. 
* Set formula_1 is many-one reducible to formula_2 if there is a total computable function formula_74 such that an element formula_67 is in formula_1 if and only if formula_77 is in formula_2. Such a function can be used to generate a Turing reduction (by computing formula_77, querying the oracle, and then interpreting the result).
* A truth table reduction or a weak truth table reduction must present all of its oracle queries at the same time. In a truth table reduction, the reduction also gives a boolean function (a truth table) that, when given the answers to the queries, will produce the final answer of the reduction. In a weak truth table reduction, the reduction uses the oracle answers as a basis for further computation depending on the given answers (but not using the oracle). Equivalently, a weak truth table reduction is one for which the use of the reduction is bounded by a computable function. For this reason, weak truth table reductions are sometimes called &quot;bounded Turing&quot; reductions.

The second way to produce a stronger reducibility notion is to limit the computational resources that the program implementing the Turing reduction may use. These limits on the computational complexity of the reduction are important when studying subrecursive classes such as P. A set &quot;A&quot; is polynomial-time reducible to a set formula_2 if there is a Turing reduction of formula_1 to formula_2 that runs in polynomial time. The concept of log-space reduction is similar.

These reductions are stronger in the sense that they provide a finer distinction into equivalence classes, and satisfy more restrictive requirements than Turing reductions. Consequently, such reductions are harder to find. There may be no way to build a many-one reduction from one set to another even when a Turing reduction for the same sets exists.

== Weaker reductions ==

According to the Church–Turing thesis, a Turing reduction is the most general form of an effectively calculable reduction. Nevertheless, weaker reductions are also considered. Set formula_1 is said to be arithmetical in formula_2 if formula_1 is definable by a formula of Peano arithmetic with formula_2 as a parameter. The set formula_1 is hyperarithmetical in formula_2 if there is a recursive ordinal formula_89 such that formula_1 is computable from formula_91, the &quot;α&quot;-iterated Turing jump of formula_2. The notion of relative constructibility is an important reducibility notion in set theory.

